A Kano Satate High Court presided over by Justice Ahmed Badamosi yesterday stopped Governor Abdullahi Ganduje from establishing Kano State Council of Chiefs and appointing its members. Ganduje had on Monday appointed the Emir of Kano, Malam Muhammad Sanusi II, as chairman of the council on two years tenure, while the chairmanship position will rotate between the five Emirate Councils. Badamosi  granted an order of interim injunction restraining the third respondent, Abdullahi Ganduje from taking away the functions and powers of the Applicants under the Kano State Emirates Council Law, 2019. The other was granted upon hearing of a motion ex parte filed by counsel to the plaintiffs, Suraj Sa’eda (SAN),  dated December 9, attached with court processes as well as exhibits. The Court however adjourned to 17th December for hearing of the motion on notice. According to the plaintiffs in the suit, the Kano Sate Emirate Kingmakers are Yusuf Nabahani (Madakin Kano), Abdullahi Sarki Ibrahim (Makama Kano), Bello Abubakar (Sarkin Dawaki Mai Tuta) and Muktar Adnan ( Sarkin Ban Kano). While the defendants in the suit are the speaker, Kano State House of Assembly, first respondent, Kano State House of Assembly, second respondent, governor of Kano State, third respondent, attorney general of Kano State, fourth respondent, Tafida Abubakar Ila, fifth respondent, Ibrahim Abdulkadir Gaya sixth respondent, Ibrahim Abubakar, seventh respondent, and Aminu Ado Bayero, eight respondent.